  <h1>Anxiety</h1>
 <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSBIIKamfRZ1M5ZPGOzBZ1R1sK0t5_l3EZPJTVlkgyWRNRvCWGnRuBm3zGME11GPHTSWww:https://www.openaccessgovernment.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/OAG-Figure_Redrawn.jpg&usqp=CAU" alt="Brain">
  <h3>Definition of Anxiety:</h3>
  <p> It's a feeling of worry, nervousness, or unease, typically about an imminent event or something with an uncertain outcome. </p>
 
  <h3> Statistics of who suffer from the mental health issue</h3>
 <p> Around 40 million adults are affected by a anxiety disorder in the United States which is 18.1% of the population every year. Anxiety disorders are highly treatable, yet only 36.9% of those suffering receive treatment.  </p>
   <img src=""
   
  <h3>What part of the body does it generally affect?</h3>
   <p> Brain and nervous system</p>
  
  <h2> All possible effects on the body </h2>
  <p> Involuntary jerking or writhing movements (chorea)Muscle problems, such as rigidity or muscle contracture (dystonia)Slow or abnormal eye movements.Impaired gait, posture and balance.Difficulty with speech or swallowing.difficulty concentrating.memory lapses.depression – including low mood, a lack of interest in things,, and feelings of hopelessness.stumbling and clumsiness.mood swings, such as irritability or aggressive behavior.</p>
  <img src="" alt="What it effects">

  <h1>Cause of disorder</h1>
  
  <h3> What happens in the body to cause the disease? </h3>
   <p>  Huntington's disease is a mutation on the 4th chromosome which is dominant and codes for the huntington's protein, which is were the disorder gets it's name from. What the original purpose Huntington's protein is unknown. </p>
  <img src="https://www.alz.org/media/HomeOffice/Inline%20Image/dementia-types-huntingtons-disease-inlineimage.jpg" alt="What it effects">

  <h2>  How is it inherited? </h2>
  
  <h3> Is it sex-linked? What type of genetic inheritance is it? </h3>
  <p>Its a sex-linked disorder and is caused by a single deficient gene on the 4th chromosome. The defect is dominant. Codes for the Huntington's protein.</p>
    <img src="https://www.cisbio.eu/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Blogpost-huntingtons-disease-molecular-consequences.svg" alt="How it's cuased">

  <h2>How is the disorder treated and how is it diagnosed? </h2>
  <p> Physical therapy helps improve quality of life through prescribed exercise, hands-on care, and patient education.  Xenazine helps with reducing sporadic and involuntary movements, Austedo helps reduce the implications that are from Huntington's disease.</p>
    <img src="https://img.collegedekhocdn.com/media/img/careers/doctor-clinic.jpg" alt="How it's cuased">
  
  <h3> What tests are done? Is genetic counseling an option?</h2]3>
   <p>Genetics testing and Yes</p>
  <img src="https://labblog.uofmhealth.org/sites/lab/files/2018-09/michigan-med-l-aging-gene-01.jpg" alt="How it's cuased">
  
  <h3> How common it is? </h3>
  <p> Fewer than 200,000 US cases per year </p>
   <img src="https://www.mayoclinic.org/-/media/kcms/gbs/patient-consumer/images/2013/11/15/17/37/r7_autosomaldominantthu_jpg.jpg" alt="How it's cuased">
  
   <h3> Is it more common in a certain group of people? </h3>
  <p> Yes, 3 to 7 people per 100,000 people have it with a European ancestry. </p>

  <h2> What I learned </h2>
  
  <p> That Huntington's disease is caused by the 4th Chromosome and that it’s a dominant trait. I also learned that it’s actually more common for people with European ancestry to have it.</p>
  
